oes the age of participation look like from the perspective of a museum visitor? Arguably, the concept of participative experiences is already so deeply ingrained in our culture that we may not even think about it as participation. Museum visitors engage in a number of activities, of which observing the exhibits is only one part. Since most visitors come to the museum together with someone else, they spend time and attention on the people they came with, and often the needs of the group are given priority over individual preferences. How can museums tap into these activities - and make themselves relevant to visitors? In this chapter we will try to approach this constructively, as a design opportunity. Could it be productive for the museum to consider itself not only as a disseminator of knowledge, but also as the facilitator of participative activities between visitors?\n  In what follows, we will outline a range of practical design projects that serve as examples of this approach. These projects were part of the European Union funded Horizon2020 project GIFT, a cross-disciplinary collaboration between researchers, artists, designers and many international museums and heritage organisations, exploring the concept of interpersonal museum experiences (see https://gifting.digital/). What the projects have in common is that they build on visitors co-creating and sharing their own narratives in the museum context. We suggest that these projects demonstrate a spectrum of possibilities: From experiences that take place almost without any museum involvement, to those that give museums a role in curating these narratives.\n\nPublished: 2018-06-24\nTitle: Artwork Identification from Wearable Camera Images for Enhancing Experience of Museum Audiences\nAuthors: Rui Zhang, Yusuf Tas, Piotr Koniusz\nSummary: Recommendation systems based on image recognition could prove a vital tool in enhancing the experience of museum audiences. However, for practical systems utilizing wearable cameras, a number of challenges exist which affect the quality of image recognition. In this pilot study, we focus on recognition of museum collections by using a wearable camera in three different museum spaces. We discuss the application of wearable cameras, and the practical and technical challenges in devising a robust system that can recognize artworks viewed by the visitors to create a detailed record of their visit. Specifically, to illustrate the impact of different kinds of museum spaces on image recognition, we collect three training datasets of museum exhibits containing variety of paintings, clocks, and sculptures. Subsequently, we equip selected visitors with wearable cameras to capture artworks viewed by them as they stroll along exhibitions. We use Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) which are pre-trained on the ImageNet dataset and fine-tuned on each of the training sets for the purpose of artwork identification. In the testing stage, we use CNNs to identify artworks captured by the visitors with a wearable camera. We analyze the accuracy of their recognition and provide an insight into the applicability of such a system to further engage audiences with museum exhibitions.\n\nPublished: 2020-12-25\nTitle: Validation and Comparison of Instrumented Mouthguards for Measuring Head Kinematics and Assessing Brain Deformation in Football Impacts\nAuthors: Yuzhe Liu, August G. Domel, Seyed Abdolmajid Yousefsani, Jovana Kondic, Gerald Grant, Michael Zeineh, David B. Camarillo\nSummary: Because of the relatively rigid coupling between the upper dentition and the skull, instrumented mouthguards have been shown to be a viable way of measuring head impact kinematics for assisting in understanding the underlying biomechanics of concussions. This has led various companies and institutions to furt\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://gifting.digital/] ---\nTitle: The GIFT Box\n\nURL Source: https://gifting.digital/\n\nMarkdown Content:\nThe GIFT Box\n===============\n', name='academic_search', id='ab8c3a02-9e0f-4fe8-b458-293f549c2455', tool_call_id='call_edf13f3b32de456b896f1a20'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 117, 'prompt_tokens': 10294, 'total_tokens': 10411, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 117}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 10294}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-37a867c8-9b0a-9108-8ea0-cbf3674e7cf1', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dc5-f57e-7090-9df7-cb4d857bb54e-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'crawl_tool', 'args': {'__arg1': 'https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E8%8B%8F%E6%A0%BC%E5%85%B0%E5%9B%BD%E5%AE%B6%E9%87%87%E7%9F%BF%E5%8D%9A%E7%89%A9%E9%A6%86/7205803'}, 'id': 'call_684e2259482042749788aa0f', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 10294, 'output_tokens': 117, 'total_tokens': 10411, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content="Error scraping https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E8%8B%8F%E6%A0%BC%E5%85%B0%E5%9B%BD%E5%AE%B6%E9%87%87%E7%9F%BF%E5%8D%9A%E7%89%A9%E9%A6%86/7205803: HTTPSConnectionPool(host='r.jina.ai', port=443): Read timed out. (read timeout=10)", name='crawl_tool', id='8c8c2acc-e380-4728-8f84-31c5c39fd642', tool_call_id='call_684e2259482042749788aa0f'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 44, 'prompt_tokens': 10542, 'total_tokens': 10586, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 44}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 10542}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-021dd972-4314-9182-a152-b7d6ad6e3a72', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dc6-25dc-7b42-98c3-64cd637fd270-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'common_search', 'args': {'query': '"ornate circular white label" blue border number 32 Scotland museum football'}, 'id': 'call_4103acf04ff84df1b14b42ff', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 10542, 'output_tokens': 44, 'total_tokens': 10586, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content="SYSTEM ALERT: You have used the tool 'common_search' 3 times, which is the limit for a single tool. You MUST switch to a DIFFERENT search tool (e.g., use 'academic_search' or 'web_search' instead of 'common_search'). Using the same tool repeatedly is ineffective. TRY ANOTHER TOOL.", name='common_search', id='71e8700b-677c-407d-b041-318f75c34b98', tool_call_id='call_4103acf04ff84df1b14b42ff'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 41, 'prompt_tokens': 10668, 'total_tokens': 10709, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 41}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 10668}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-481c103d-5dc9-9951-807a-c07825ecac49', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dc6-32dd-7cf2-bb1e-1952cda5557b-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'academic_search', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Scotland museum football artifact "number 32" label'}, 'id': 'call_ff343ca53b4a4e61b4331750', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 10668, 'output_tokens': 41, 'total_tokens': 10709, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content="Published: 2004-10-06\nTitle: Disabled Access for Museum Websites\nAuthors: Jonathan P. Bowen\nSummary: Physical disabled access is something that most museums consider very seriously. Indeed, there are normally legal requirements to do so. However, online disabled access is still a relatively novel field. Most museums have not yet considered the issues in depth. The Human-Computer Interface for their websites is normally tested with major browsers, but not with specialist browsers or against the relevant accessibility and validation standards. We consider the current state of the art in this area and mention an accessibility survey of some museum websites.\n\nPublished: 2023-12-21\nTitle: Subtle Sound Design: Designing for experience blend in a historic house museum\nAuthors: Mia F. Yates, Anders Sundnes Løvlie\nSummary: In this article, we present and discuss a user-study prototype, developed for Bakkehuset historic house museum in Copenhagen. We examine how the prototype - a digital sound installation - can expand visitors' experiences of the house and offer encounters with immaterial cultural heritage. Historic house museums often hold back on utilizing digital communication tools inside the houses, since a central purpose of this type of museum is to preserve an original environment. Digital communication tools however hold great potential for facilitating rich encounters with cultural heritage and in particular with the immaterial aspects of museum collections and their histories. In this article we present our design steps and choices, aiming at subtly and seamlessly adding a digital dimension to a historic house. Based on qualitative interviews, we evaluate how the sound installation at Bakkehuset is sensed, interpreted, and used by visitors as part of their museum experience. In turn, we shed light on the historic house museum as a distinct design context for designing hybrid visitor experiences and point to the potentials of digital communication tools in this context.\n\nPublished: 2020-12-25\nTitle: Validation and Comparison of Instrumented Mouthguards for Measuring Head Kinematics and Assessing Brain Deformation in Football Impacts\nAuthors: Yuzhe Liu, August G. Domel, Seyed Abdolmajid Yousefsani, Jovana Kondic, Gerald Grant, Michael Zeineh, David B. Camarillo\nSummary: Because of the relatively rigid coupling between the upper dentition and the skull, instrumented mouthguards have been shown to be a viable way of measuring head impact kinematics for assisting in understanding the underlying biomechanics of concussions. This has led various companies and institutions to further develop instrumented mouthguards. However, their use as a research tool for understanding concussive impacts makes quantification of their accuracy critical, especially given the conflicting results from various recent studies. Here we present a study that uses a pneumatic impactor to deliver impacts characteristic to football to a Hybrid III headform, in order to validate and compare five of the most commonly used instrumented mouthguards. We found that all tested mouthguards gave accurate measurements for the peak angular acceleration (mean relative error, MRE < 13%), the peak angular velocity (MRE < 8%), brain injury criteria values (MRE < 13%) and brain deformation (described as maximum principal strain and fiber strain, calculated by a convolutional neural network based brain model, MRE < 9%). Finally, we found that the accuracy of the measurement varies with the impact locations yet is not sensitive to the impact velocity for the most part.", name='academic_search', id='ab473d1b-0fd2-4418-b130-6d95245affab', tool_call_id='call_ff343ca53b4a4e61b4331750'), AIMessage(content='# Research Report: Scottish Football Heritage Sites Investigation\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nThis research investigates a complex puzzle involving Scottish football heritage sites and museums. The goal is to determine the opening year of the first five-star accredited place based on the following criteria:\n- A five-star accredited place opened at a five-star accredited venue\n- The venue is in a city hosting an organization that manages the venue\n- An exhibition about mining communities\' traits shaping football development, funded by Museums Galleries Scotland\n- The exhibition is not in the host city\n- Another five-star accredited place houses an artifact described as "an ornate circular white label with a blue border number 32"\n- Both places collaborate with the same organization\n\n## Research Findings\n\n### Scottish Football Museum and Hampden Park\n\nThe Scottish Football Museum is Scotland\'s national football museum, located at Hampden Park in Glasgow. The museum houses extensive collections related to Scottish football history, including the world\'s oldest international football cap and match tickets, as well as the Scottish Cup, the world\'s oldest national football trophy. The museum also features the Scottish Football Hall of Fame and offers stadium tours of Hampden Park, which serves as the home of the Scottish national football team.\n\nGlasgow appears to be the host city for this football heritage organization, with Hampden Park being the five-star accredited venue that houses the Scottish Football Museum.\n\n### National Mining Museum Scotland\n\nThe National Mining Museum Scotland is located in Newtongrange, Midlothian, at the Lady Victoria Colliery site. This museum is situated in a preserved Victorian-era coal mine that opened in 1895 as Scotland\'s first super pit and closed in 1981 before being converted into a museum. The museum is not located in Glasgow, which aligns with the puzzle\'s requirement that the exhibition place is "not situated in that city."\n\nThe museum features exhibits on steam winding engines, Lancashire boiler units, and wooden dredging machines, representing Scotland\'s mining heritage.\n\n### Museums Galleries Scotland Accreditation\n\nMuseums Galleries Scotland is the organization responsible for museum accreditation in Scotland. This body provides funding and accreditation services to museums across Scotland, including the five-star accreditation scheme mentioned in the puzzle. National Museums Scotland, based in Edinburgh, is confirmed as a five-star accredited museum that received the 2020 TripAdvisor "Travelers\' Choice" award and other recognitions.\n\n### Missing Information\n\nDespite extensive searching, the following critical information could not be located:\n- The specific exhibition about mining communities\' traits shaping football development funded by Museums Galleries Scotland\n- The artifact described as "an ornate circular white label with a blue border number 32"\n- The exact opening year of the first five-star accredited place in this context\n- Specific collaboration details between the museums and the organizing body\n\nThe search results did not provide sufficient detail about the connection between mining communities and football development exhibitions, nor could the specific artifact with the number 32 label be identified in any of the searched sources.\n\n### Key Locations Identified\n\n| Location | City | Type | Status |\n|----------|------|------|--------|\n| Scottish Football Museum | Glasgow | Football Museum | Five-star accredited venue |\n| National Mining Museum Scotland | Newtongrange, Midlothian | Mining Museum | Not in host city |\n| National Museums Scotland | Edinburgh | National Museum | Five-star accredited |\n\n## Conclusion\n\nBased on the research conducted, I was able to identify several key Scottish museum venues related to football and mining heritage. The Scottish Football Museum at Hampden Park in Glasgow and the National Mining Museum Scotland in Newtongrange are confirmed locations that match some criteria of the puzzle. Museums Galleries Scotland is confirmed as the accreditation and funding body for Scottish museums.\n\nHowever, due to limitations in the search results, I cannot definitively determine the opening year of the first five-star accredited place as described in the puzzle. The specific exhibition about mining communities\' influence on football development and the artifact with the "ornate circular white label with blue border number 32" could not be located in the available search results.\n\nThe National Mining Museum Scotland opened after the colliery closed in 1981, but the exact opening year as a museum was not confirmed in the search results. The Scottish Football Museum\'s opening date was also not explicitly stated in the available sources.\n\n**Note**: This report is based on the information gathered from the available search tools. Additional research with more specific search queries or access to museum databases would be required to obtain the definitive opening year and complete the puzzle accurately.\n\n## References\n\n- [苏格兰国家博物馆](https://m.baike.com/wikiid/7247142425554485306)\n\n- [格拉斯哥的最佳博物馆](https://tripomatic.com/zh/list/glasgow-de-zui-jia-bo-wu-guan-city:108)\n\n- [苏格兰国家采矿博物馆](https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E8%8B%8F%E6%A0%BC%E5%85%B0%E5%9B%BD%E5%AE%B6%E9%87%87%E7%9F%BF%E5%8D%9A%E7%89%A9%E9%A6%86/7205803)\n\n- [苏格兰足球博物馆](https://baike.baidu.com/item/%E8%8B%8F%E6%A0%BC%E5%85%B0%E8%B6%B3%E7%90%83%E5%8D%9A%E7%89%A9%E9%A6%86/16998250)\n\n- [格拉斯哥苏格兰足球博物馆游玩攻略](https://gs.ctrip.com/html5/you/sight/glasgow713/1687805.html)\n\n- [苏格兰第二站，汉普顿公园球场，一座也许你不熟悉的五星球场](https://sports8.cc/xinwen/201879.html)\n\n- [英伦之旅（四）](https://m.meipian.cn/5aruy9wv)\n\n- [苏格兰国家博物馆](https://web.hnmuseum.com/fr/node/861)', additional_kwargs={}, response_metadata={}, name='researcher', id='0be8acd4-a755-4dd1-bcf0-4044bd5a623a', tool_calls=[], invalid_tool_calls=[]), HumanMessage(content='# Research Topic\n\nScottish Football Heritage Sites Research Plan\n\n# Completed Research Steps\n\n## Comple