ms Galleries Scotland'}, 'id': 'call_1a1928da74d6440a888c0bd9', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 8358, 'output_tokens': 247, 'total_tokens': 8605, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 206}}), ToolMessage(content="Published: 2015-11-19\nTitle: Rectification of position data of Scotland in Ptolemy's Geographike Hyphegesis\nAuthors: Christian Marx\nSummary: The ancient geographic coordinates given for places of Great Britain in Ptolemy's Geographike Hyphegesis are investigated by means of geodetic methods. The turning of Scotland to the east is modelled by a three-dimensional rotation. On the basis of different data sets of control points, the parameters of the rotation are estimated by means of methods of adjustment theory. Furthermore, a geodetic-statistical analysis method is applied to Scotland, by which groups of places of homogenous distortions and modern counterparts of the ancient places are determined. Based on the results of the investigations, answers are given for questions concerning Ptolemaic positions unsolved so far.\n\nPublished: 2021-09-20\nTitle: A mixed-methods ethnographic approach to participatory budgeting in Scotland\nAuthors: Jonathan Davies, M. Arana-Catania, Rob Procter, F. A. Van Lier, Yulan He\nSummary: Participatory budgeting (PB) is already well established in Scotland in the form of community led grant-making yet has recently transformed from a grass-roots activity to a mainstream process or embedded 'policy instrument'. An integral part of this turn is the use of the Consul digital platform as the primary means of citizen participation. Using a mixed method approach, this ongoing research paper explores how each of the 32 local authorities that make up Scotland utilise the Consul platform to engage their citizens in the PB process and how they then make sense of citizens' contributions. In particular, we focus on whether natural language processing (NLP) tools can facilitate both citizen engagement, and the processes by which citizens' contributions are analysed and translated into policies.\n\nPublished: 2020-11-24\nTitle: Designing for Interpersonal Museum Experiences\nAuthors: Anders Sundnes Løvlie, Lina Eklund, Annika Waern, Karin Ryding, Paulina Rajkowska\nSummary: What does the age of participation look like from the perspective of a museum visitor? Arguably, the concept of participative experiences is already so deeply ingrained in our culture that we may not even think about it as participation. Museum visitors engage in a number of activities, of which observing the exhibits is only one part. Since most visitors come to the museum together with someone else, they spend time and attention on the people they came with, and often the needs of the group are given priority over individual preferences. How can museums tap into these activities - and make themselves relevant to visitors? In this chapter we will try to approach this constructively, as a design opportunity. Could it be productive for the museum to consider itself not only as a disseminator of knowledge, but also as the facilitator of participative activities between visitors?\n  In what follows, we will outline a range of practical design projects that serve as examples of this approach. These projects were part of the European Union funded Horizon2020 project GIFT, a cross-disciplinary collaboration between researchers, artists, designers and many international museums and heritage organisations, exploring the concept of interpersonal museum experiences (see https://gifting.digital/). What the projects have in common is that they build on visitors co-creating and sharing their own narratives in the museum context. We suggest that these projects demonstrate a spectrum of possibilities: From experiences that take place almost without any museum involvement, to those that give museums a role in curating these narratives.\n\n--- [Automatic Crawl of Top Result: https://gifting.digital/] ---\nTitle: The GIFT Box\n\nURL Source: https://gifting.digital/\n\nMarkdown Content:\nThe GIFT Box\n===============\n", name='academic_search', id='a3a6e8a7-24ab-4e96-80af-3c5435636e7e', tool_call_id='call_1a1928da74d6440a888c0bd9'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 33, 'prompt_tokens': 9206, 'total_tokens': 9239, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 33}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 9206}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmpl-8caeb1bc-1d48-965a-ae09-4918c7c319af', 'finish_reason': 'tool_calls', 'logprobs': None}, name='researcher', id='lc_run--019c9dc5-c104-7230-898a-f52dd8831b38-0', tool_calls=[{'name': 'wikipedia', 'args': {'__arg1': 'Scottish Football Museum'}, 'id': 'call_46ef0dd951a2458fb1e583b8', 'type': 'tool_call'}], invalid_tool_calls=[], usage_metadata={'input_tokens': 9206, 'output_tokens': 33, 'total_tokens': 9239, 'input_token_details': {}, 'output_token_details': {'reasoning': 0}}), ToolMessage(content='Error performing Wikipedia search: Expecting value: line 1 column 1 (char 0)', name='wikipedia', id='ef610c26-a14c-408c-ba68-bf2c3bb813b5', tool_call_id='call_46ef0dd951a2458fb1e583b8'), AIMessage(content='', additional_kwargs={'refusal': None}, response_metadata={'token_usage': {'completion_tokens': 43, 'prompt_tokens': 9273, 'total_tokens': 9316, 'completion_tokens_details': {'accepted_prediction_tokens': None, 'audio_tokens': None, 'reasoning_tokens': 0, 'rejected_prediction_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 43}, 'prompt_tokens_details': {'audio_tokens': None, 'cached_tokens': None, 'text_tokens': 9273}}, 'model_provider': 'openai', 'model_name': 'qwen3.5-plus', 'system_fingerprint': None, 'id': 'chatcmp